# nyne-navigate — Scoped Reading & Exploration

Efficient code navigation through nyne's virtual filesystem. Every recognized source file
gains an `@/` namespace containing its decomposed structure. Use these virtual paths instead
of reading raw files — scoped reads return only the relevant code, saving ~90% of context tokens.

## Core Principle: Never Read Raw Source Files

Reading a 400-line file to find a 25-line function wastes 94% of consumed tokens. Always
use the VFS decomposition:

| Instead of | Use | Token savings |
|-|-|-|
| `Read file.{{ ext }}` (400 lines) | `Read file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/OVERVIEW.md` → targeted symbol | ~90% |
| `Grep "fn process" src/` | `ls file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/by-kind/fn/` | exact matches only |
| `Read file.{{ ext }}` + scan for imports | `Read file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/imports.{{ ext }}` | ~95% |

## Exploration Workflow

### Step 1: Start with OVERVIEW.md

For any unfamiliar file, read its symbol overview first:

```sh
cat file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/OVERVIEW.md
```

Returns a symbol table with:
- Symbol names and kinds (function, struct, impl, trait, etc.)
- Line ranges in the source file
- **Token estimates** per symbol — use these to budget context window before reading

For directory-level exploration:

```sh
cat dir@/OVERVIEW.md          # aggregated symbols across all files in directory
```

### Step 2: Read Specific Symbols

Use the shorthand for the most common operation (reading a body):

```sh
cat file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/process.{{ ext }}           # shorthand — returns body only
cat file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/Foo~Impl@/new.{{ ext }}     # nested method shorthand
```

Or access specific aspects:

```sh
cat file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/process@/body.{{ ext }}        # function body
cat file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/process@/signature.{{ ext }}   # declaration line only
cat file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/process@/docstring.txt  # docstring only
cat file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/Foo~Impl@/OVERVIEW.md   # child symbols of an impl block
```

### Step 3: Filter by Kind

For large files with many symbols, filter by kind:

```sh
ls file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/by-kind/fn/       # all functions
ls file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/by-kind/struct/   # all structs
ls file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/by-kind/impl/     # all impl blocks
```

Entries are symlinks back to the symbol directories.

### Step 4: Understand Relationships (Before Modifying)

**Before modifying any symbol**, read its relationships:

```sh
cat file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/Foo@/CALLERS.md      # who calls this? (inline code context)
cat file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/Foo@/DEPS.md         # what does this call?
cat file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/Foo@/REFERENCES.md   # all usage sites
```

These replace grep-based searches. One read each, with full code context at every site.

## Path Patterns Quick Reference

### Naming Conventions

| Pattern | Meaning |
|-|-|
| `symbols/my_function.{{ ext }}` | Top-level symbol (shorthand for body) |
| `symbols/Foo~Struct.{{ ext }}` | Disambiguated by kind (collision with `Foo~Impl`) |
| `symbols/Trait_for_Type.{{ ext }}` | Trait/interface implementation |
| `symbols/Foo~Impl@/new.{{ ext }}` | Nested method inside impl block |
| `UPPERCASE.md` | Read-only, template-generated |
| `lowercase.ext` | Read/writable metadata |
| `Name@/` | Symbol scope container |

### File-Level Virtual Files

```
file.ext@/OVERVIEW.md              # symbol table with token estimates
file.ext@/DIAGNOSTICS.md           # LSP diagnostics (instant, no build needed)
file.ext@/lines                    # all lines (read, write replaces file, append to EOF)
file.ext@/lines:M                  # single line (read, write, rm deletes line)
file.ext@/lines:M-N                # line range (read, write, rm deletes range)
file.ext@/symbols/Foo@/edit/          # per-symbol batch edit staging area
file.ext@/symbols/Foo@/edit/replace   # stage: replace symbol body (write content)
file.ext@/symbols/Foo@/edit/delete    # stage: delete symbol (write any content)
file.ext@/symbols/Foo@/edit/insert-after  # stage: insert after symbol (write content)
file.ext@/symbols/Foo@/edit/insert-before # stage: insert before symbol (write content)
file.ext@/symbols/Foo@/edit/append    # stage: append as last child (scope symbols only)
file.ext@/symbols/Foo@/edit/staged.diff   # preview staged edits (cat), apply (rm)
file.ext@/symbols/Foo@/edit/staged/   # individual staged action diffs (rm to remove)
```
### Symbol-Level Virtual Files

```
file.ext@/symbols/imports.{{ ext }}       # import block (read, write, append)
file.ext@/symbols/docstring.txt    # module-level docstring
file.ext@/symbols/Foo@/body.{{ ext }}     # symbol body
file.ext@/symbols/Foo@/signature.{{ ext }}    # declaration line
file.ext@/symbols/Foo@/docstring.txt   # symbol docstring
file.ext@/symbols/Foo@/OVERVIEW.md     # child symbol listing
file.ext@/symbols/at-line/N        # symlink to narrowest symbol at line N (lookup-only)
```

### LSP-Powered Symbol Files

```
file.ext@/symbols/Foo@/CALLERS.md       # who calls this (inline code context)
file.ext@/symbols/Foo@/DEPS.md          # what this calls (inline code context)
file.ext@/symbols/Foo@/REFERENCES.md    # all reference sites
file.ext@/symbols/Foo@/DOC.md           # hover documentation
file.ext@/symbols/Foo@/HINTS.md         # inlay hints (inferred types)
file.ext@/symbols/Foo@/actions/         # code actions as .diff files
file.ext@/symbols/Foo@/rename/new.diff  # rename preview (lookup-only)
file.ext@/symbols/Foo@/callers/         # symlinks to caller symbol directories
file.ext@/symbols/Foo@/deps/            # symlinks to dependency symbol directories
file.ext@/symbols/Foo@/references/      # symlinks to reference symbol directories
```

## Deleting Symbols and Line Ranges

Remove a symbol from its source file via `rmdir` on its scope container:

```sh
rmdir file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/Foo@/     # deletes Foo from source file
rm file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/Foo.{{ ext }}  # shorthand — same effect
```

The symbol's source code (decorators + docstring + signature + body) is spliced
out. Trailing blank lines are consumed. The real file is rewritten in place —
inotify propagates the change automatically.

**Delete a line range** (when symbol-level deletion isn't granular enough):

```sh
rm file.{{ ext }}@/lines:10-20          # splices out lines 10-20
```

**Inline deletions** (removing a specific aspect without deleting the whole symbol):

```sh
echo "" > file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/Foo@/docstring.txt   # truncate clears docstring
```

## Line-to-Symbol Lookup

Given a line number (from diagnostics, grep, blame, etc.), resolve it to the
enclosing symbol:

```sh
readlink file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/at-line/42    # → ../../process@/body.{{ ext }}
cat file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/at-line/42         # follows symlink, reads the body
```

Line numbers are 1-based (matching source file line numbers). The symlink
targets the narrowest (most deeply nested) symbol containing that line.
This is lookup-only — entries don't appear in `readdir`.

## Symlink Traversal

LSP symlinks in `callers/`, `deps/`, `references/`, etc. point directly to symbol
directories. Follow them to traverse the codebase without resolving file paths:

```sh
# Read a caller's body via symlink — no need to know which file it lives in
cat file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/process@/callers/init.{{ ext }}
# resolves to → main.{{ ext }}@/symbols/init@/body.{{ ext }}

# Edit through symlinks — same path
Edit file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/process@/callers/init.{{ ext }}

# List all callees of a function
ls file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/process@/deps/

# Check actions available on a caller
ls file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/process@/callers/init/actions/
```

The `.{{ ext }}` shorthand works through symlinks — `callers/init.{{ ext }}` resolves to the caller's
body. Edit through symlinks the same way.

## Markdown Documents

Markdown files decompose at headers into navigable sections:

```sh
cat doc.md@/symbols/OVERVIEW.md                  # section listing
cat doc.md@/symbols/20-getting-started.md        # read one section
cat doc.md@/symbols/20-getting-started/code/10.{{ ext }}   # extracted code block
```

Section filenames use 10-increment numeric prefixes. Fenced code blocks are extracted as
editable files with extensions from the fence language tag.

## Token Budgeting

OVERVIEW.md includes token estimates per symbol. Use these to plan reads:

1. Read `OVERVIEW.md` — scan token counts
2. Read small symbols directly (< 100 tokens)
3. For large symbols, read `signature.{{ ext }}` first to confirm relevance
4. Read `body.{{ ext }}` only when the implementation is needed

## Anti-Patterns

| Anti-pattern | Correct approach |
|-|-|
| `Read file.{{ ext }}` then scan for a function | `Read file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/OVERVIEW.md` → `Read file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/fn_name.{{ ext }}` |
| `Grep "fn process" src/` to find symbols | `ls file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/by-kind/fn/` or read `OVERVIEW.md` |
| `Grep "fn process" src/` to find callers | `cat file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/process@/CALLERS.md` |
| Reading a full file to check imports | `Read file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/imports.{{ ext }}` |
| Reading a file to count symbols | `Read file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/OVERVIEW.md` (includes counts) |
| Reading caller files to understand call sites | `Read file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/Foo@/CALLERS.md` (inline code context) |
| Editing raw file to remove a function | `rmdir file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/Foo@/` (splices out, one call) |
| Grep + manual line math to find a symbol | `readlink file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/at-line/42` (instant lookup) |
| `cargo check` to verify after edits | `cat file.{{ ext }}@/DIAGNOSTICS.md` (instant, no build) |

